  "text": "# Kubernetes Controller Runtime Reconciler Registration\n\n## Overview\n\nThe controller-runtime library (sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime) provides a standardized framework for building Kubernetes controllers in Go. The controller registration process involves three main components: the Reconciler interface, the Manager, and the Builder pattern.\n\n## Core Components\n\n### 1. Reconciler Interface\n**Location**: `vendor/sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime/pkg/reconcile/reconcile.go` (lines 92-105)\n\nThe `Reconciler` interface is the core abstraction that all controllers must implement:\n\n```go\ntype Reconciler interface {\n\tReconcile(context.Context, Request) (Result, error)\n}\n```\n\nEach reconciler receives a `Request` containing the namespace and name of the object to reconcile, and returns a `Result` indicating whether requeuing is needed, along with any error.\n\n### 2. Manager Interface\n**Location**: `vendor/sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime/pkg/manager/manager.go` (lines 52-98)\n\nThe `Manager` interface initializes shared dependencies (caches, clients) and manages controller lifecycle:\n\n```go\ntype Manager interface {\n\tcluster.Cluster\n\tAdd(Runnable) error\n\tElected() <-chan struct{}\n\tAddMetricsServerExtraHandler(path string, handler http.Handler) error\n\tAddHealthzCheck(name string, check healthz.Checker) error\n\tAddReadyzCheck(name string, check healthz.Checker) error\n\tStart(ctx context.Context) error\n\tGetWebhookServer() webhook.Server\n\tGetLogger() logr.Logger\n\tGetControllerOptions() config.Controller\n}\n```\n\nThe Manager is instantiated using `manager.New(config *rest.Config, options Options)` which sets up the controller runtime with caches, clients, and other shared infrastructure.\n\n### 3. Builder Pattern\n**Location**: `vendor/sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime/pkg/builder/controller.go` (lines 54-65)\n\nThe `Builder` struct provides a fluent API for configuring controllers:\n\n```go\ntype Builder struct {\n\tforInput         ForInput\n\townsInput        []OwnsInput\n\trawSources       []source.Source\n\twatchesInput     []WatchesInput\n\tmgr              manager.Manager\n\tglobalPredicates []predicate.Predicate\n\tctrl             controller.Controller\n\tctrlOptions      controller.Options\n\tname             string\n}\n```\n\n## Controller Registration Flow\n\n### Step 1: Create a Manager\nControllers are created by first instantiating a Manager:\n```go\nmgr, err := manager.New(config, options)\n```\n\n### Step 2: Create a Controller Builder\nA builder is created using `ControllerManagedBy()` (line 68-70):\n```go\nbuilder := ControllerManagedBy(mgr)\n```\n\n### Step 3: Configure the Controller\nThe builder is configured using chain methods:\n- `.For(object)` (lines 84-96) - Specifies the primary object type to reconcile\n- `.Owns(object)` (lines 114-122) - Specifies owned object types\n- `.Watches(object, handler)` (lines 137-149) - Specifies additional objects to watch\n- `.WithEventFilter(predicate)` (lines 200-203) - Sets event filters\n- `.Named(name)` (lines 222-225) - Sets the controller name\n\n### Step 4: Complete/Build the Controller\nThe controller is registered via one of two methods:\n\n**Complete()** (lines 228-231):\n```go\nerr := builder.Complete(reconciler)\n```\n\n**Build()** (lines 234-256):\n```go\nctrl, err := builder.Build(reconciler)\n```\n\nBoth methods validate the configuration, create the controller via `newController()` (which is `controller.New` at line 40), and set up watches via `doWatch()` (lines 275-338).\n\n### Step 5: Start the Manager\nFinally, the manager starts all registered controllers:\n```go\nerr := mgr.Start(ctx)\n```\n\n## SetupWithManager Pattern (Recommended Usage)\n\nThe controller-runtime framework encourages the SetupWithManager pattern where controllers implement a method that registers themselves:\n\n```go\nfunc (r *MyReconciler) SetupWithManager(mgr ctrl.Manager) error {\n\treturn ctrl.NewControllerManagedBy(mgr).\n\t\tFor(&myv1.MyResource{}).\n\t\tOwns(&corev1.Pod{}).\n\t\tComplete(r)\n}\n```\n\nThis pattern encapsulates the controller configuration within the controller itself, promoting separation of concerns and reusability.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1. **Reconcile Loop**: The manager starts all controllers which continuously watch for events and call the `Reconcile()` method for each request.\n\n2. **Event Handling**: Event sources are configured via `.For()`, `.Owns()`, and `.Watches()` methods. When objects change, corresponding reconcile requests are enqueued.\n\n3. **Level-Based Reconciliation**: Reconciliation is level-based, not event-based. The reconciler observes the current state by reading from the cache/apiserver, not from event data.\n\n4. **Workqueue Management**: The builder automatically sets up workqueues and event handlers that enqueue reconcile requests with exponential backoff on errors.\n\n5. **Manager Lifecycle**: The manager handles cache initialization, client setup, metrics/health probes, leader election, and graceful shutdown of all controllers."
